    "[Marketing] Brand Management": [
        { q: "A 'Brand' is defined as:", options: ["A legal entity", "A name, term, design, or symbol that identifies one seller's good or service as distinct from those of other sellers", "A physical product", "A pricing strategy"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Brand Equity refers to:", options: ["The total stock value of a company", "The added value endowed on products and services by the brand name", "The cost to design a logo", "The marketing budget"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Keller's Customer-Based Brand Equity (CBBE) model states that the power of a brand lies in:", options: ["Its financial backing", "What resides in the minds and hearts of customers based on their experiences", "Its physical distribution", "Its patent portfolio"], a: 1 },
        { q: "The highest level of Keller's CBBE pyramid is:", options: ["Brand Salience", "Brand Performance", "Brand Imagery", "Brand Resonance (strong psychological bond)"], a: 3 },
        { q: "Brand Awareness consists of:", options: ["Brand loyalty and satisfaction", "Brand recognition and brand recall", "Brand price and quality", "Brand name and logo"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Brand Image is formed by:", options: ["The CEO's vision", "The set of associations and beliefs consumers hold about a brand", "The factory location", "The product ingredients"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Brand Positioning is the act of:", options: ["Placing products on a supermarket shelf", "Designing the company's offering and image to occupy a distinct and valued place in the target market's mind", "Pricing the product high", "Advertising globally"], a: 1 },
        { q: "A Point of Parity (POP) in brand positioning refers to:", options: ["A unique benefit", "Attributes that are not necessarily unique to the brand but are shared with other brands (category must-haves)", "A pricing strategy", "A physical location"], a: 1 },
        { q: "A Point of Difference (POD) is:", options: ["A weakness", "Attributes or benefits that consumers strongly associate with a brand and believe they cannot find in competitors", "A neutral attribute", "A generic feature"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Brand Extension involves:", options: ["Extending the expiration date", "Using an established brand name to enter a completely new product category", "Launching a new brand in the same category", "Increasing the product size"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Line Extension involves:", options: ["Using a new brand name in a new category", "Adding new sizes, flavors, or variations under an existing brand name within the same product category", "Extending the factory line", "Extending the advertising campaign"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Co-branding is a strategy where:", options: ["Two companies merge", "Two or more well-known brands are combined into a joint product or marketed together", "A company copies a competitor's brand", "A brand is sold"], a: 1 },
        { q: "A 'Private Label' brand (or Store Brand) is:", options: ["A brand owned by an individual", "A brand created and owned by a retailer/reseller (e.g., AmazonBasics)", "A secret brand", "A luxury brand"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Brand Architecture refers to:", options: ["The physical design of the company headquarters", "The structure of brands within an organizational entity (how the corporate brand relates to sub-brands)", "The IT infrastructure", "The logo design process"], a: 1 },
        { q: "In a 'House of Brands' strategy (e.g., P&G):", options: ["All products carry the corporate name", "The corporate brand is hidden or secondary, and individual product brands are heavily promoted", "There is only one brand", "Brands are housed in a physical store"], a: 1 },
        { q: "In a 'Branded House' strategy (e.g., Virgin):", options: ["Individual products have separate names", "The corporate brand is dominant and applied across all products/services", "The brand is sold to franchisees", "The brand name is kept secret"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Brand Cannibalization occurs when:", options: ["Competitors steal market share", "A company's new product takes sales away from its own existing products", "A brand goes bankrupt", "Customers stop buying entirely"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Brand Revitalization involves:", options: ["Starting a new company", "Recapturing lost brand equity and breathing new life into a declining brand", "Lowering prices to zero", "Ignoring the brand"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Brand Audit is a comprehensive examination of a brand to:", options: ["Calculate taxes", "Assess its health, uncover its sources of brand equity, and suggest ways to improve it", "Check employee attendance", "Audit the advertising agency's bills"], a: 1 },
        { q: "Brand Personality, as defined by Jennifer Aaker, includes dimensions like:", options: ["Price, Quality, Value", "Sincerity, Excitement, Competence, Sophistication, Ruggedness", "Red, Blue, Green", "Fast, Slow, Medium"], a: 1 }
    ],
